Amber unfolded the pages and found out that it was not Kallen’s last words.

This was a farewell letter from Kallen Kaslana to Otto Apocalypse.

“Thanks for your visit and the wine you brought me.”

“But sorry, I can’t accept the choice you offered me.”

“I tried, Otto, I tried many ways to turn things around and bring justice back.”

“But Otto, we’re just too naive and too weak…”

“We were played by the old men like chess pieces, and everything we did failed to make even the slightest difference.”

“Otto, do you remember our first rogue action?”

“We were so happy and content, as if we had the solution to all the problems in the world.”

“That was the most joyful time I’ve ever spent in my life.”

“But shortly after that, we hit a wall.”

“A wall built with bricks of desire and the adhesive of power. It was erected from hell and split the world.”

“Eventually, we had to part ways before the wall.”

“I left my world behind, but I never found a new continent through which everything could be changed.”

“In the distant east, by the hands of twisted fate…”

“Just like you, I did something terribly wrong.”

“You killed your own sister Eleanor, and I… I killed her.”

“Otto, I know you’ve always looked up to me as your hero.”

“But I’m just another flawed soul with shortsightedness and confusion.”

“I’m not as great as you’ve imagined… I’m just a fool who refuses to act against my heart.”

“In your eyes, I’m stupid and stubborn, but even in the face of death, I can never betray my first motivation.”

“As long as my heart beats, my body and my mind cannot be turned into a chess piece deprived of emotions and feelings.”

“In some way, you can say I’m a selfish person.”

“Even so, I still ask for your forgiveness.”

“Since I’m hellbent on staying true to myself, there’s only one way before me.”

“I know this will break your heart.”

“But Otto, if the hero Kallen in your heart is still alive…”

“She’d tell you why she’d rather die than become a pawn in the political game.”

“So… farewell, my gifted inventor.”

“Maybe in the end, I can indeed be a hero forever in your heart.”

Amber: …

Amber: (She stayed true to herself till her last breath…)

Theresa: Amber?

Amber put the letter back into the chest and handed it to Theresa.

Amber: Thank you for finding this letter, Master Theresa.

Theresa: Huh? You sure you want me to keep the chest? Maybe Grandpa wants it too.

Amber: No, it’s better kept in your hands.

Amber: I don’t think Master Otto needs it now, and I’ve found my answer, more or less.

Amber: So, I wish you can keep the chest.

